natural problem: Caroline can make eleven lassis out of two mangoes. How many lassis can she make out of twelve mangoes?
natural solution: Multiplying both parts of the ratio by 6 gives \[\text{lassis}:\text{mangoes} = 11:2 = 66:12,\]so she can make $\boxed{66}$ lassis.

theorem

shows  "12 * lassis = 66 * mangoes"

 Multiplying both parts of the ratio by 6 gives \[\text{lassis}:\text{mangoes} = 11:2 = 66:12,\]so she can make $\boxed{66}$ lassis.
 *)

theorem
fixes lassis mangoes :: nat

 proof-
